benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/versions - Retrieve a list of catalog versions

covered: Valid Request: TC01 and TC02 validate successful retrieval (200) and response format (application/json) for global and account-scoped requests.
Empty Response: TC03 and TC13 verify behavior when no catalog versions exist (empty JSON array and no stack traces).

Query Parameters: Extensive coverage for accountId and query parameter handling (valid accountId, non-existent accountId, invalid formats, empty string, leading/trailing spaces, mixed-case, unsupported params ignored — TC02, TC04, TC05, TC09, TC16, TC17, TC18).
Authorization / Authentication: TC06 and TC07 cover missing and expired/invalid tokens (401 responses).
Error Handling: Tests cover expected client errors and server errors (400 for bad input, 500 for malformed response, 503 for service unavailable, and timeout-related behavior including 504 in TC11).
Security: SQL injection attempt is tested (TC12) and checks are included to prevent exposure of sensitive information.
Performance & Concurrency: TC10 (10,000 items, response-time expectation) and TC15 (100 concurrent requests) exercise load/performance aspects.
Content & Accessibility: TC01 and TC20 assert machine-readable JSON (application/json) and ensure no HTML/UI leakage.
gaps: Pagination: No tests for pagination or chunked responses (limit/page/offset), page links, or behavior when result sets are larger than a single response.
Caching Behavior / Conditional Requests: No tests for ETag, Last-Modified, If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since, 304 Not Modified, or Cache-Control headers.
Rate Limiting & Throttling: No explicit tests to trigger 429 Too Many Requests or to verify Retry-After/Rate-Limit headers (concurrency tests exist but do not validate throttling behavior).
Authorization scope / Forbidden (403): Tests cover 401 but not 403 or role/tenant-permission enforcement (ensuring a valid token cannot access another tenantâs catalog versions).
Content Negotiation: No tests for Accept header handling or 406 Not Acceptable behavior.
Response Ordering, Deduplication & Consistency: No checks for deterministic ordering of dates, duplicate handling, or stable pagination results across requests.
HTTP Method handling: No tests asserting other HTTP methods (POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE) return 405 Method Not Allowed.
Header validations beyond Content-Type: Missing checks for other response headers (Date, Cache-Control, ETag, Link for pagination, Retry-After for throttling).
recommendations: Add pagination tests: introduce limit/offset or page/size cases, verify correct slicing across pages, validate Link headers or total counts, and test boundary pages and consistency under concurrent reads.

Add caching/conditional-get tests: validate presence and semantics of ETag and Cache-Control/Last-Modified headers; test If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since requests to assert 304 Not Modified behavior when appropriate.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate high-frequency requests to assert 429 Too Many Requests behavior, validate Retry-After and Rate-Limit headers, and verify graceful degradation under throttling.
Add authorization-scope and 403 tests: verify that tokens lacking tenant permissions receive 403 and that tenant isolation prevents cross-tenant data access even when accountId is supplied.
Add content negotiation tests: send different Accept headers to validate correct handling and 406 behavior (or documented fallback behavior).

Add ordering, deduplication and consistency checks: assert a defined sort order of effective dates, test that duplicates are handled consistently, and verify consistent pagination ordering across requests.
Add HTTP-method validation tests: assert that non-GET methods return 405 Method Not Allowed and that allowed methods behave idempotently as documented.

Add header and leakage checks: verify presence/correctness of Date, Content-Type, Cache-Control, ETag, Link (pagination), and ensure all error responses never expose stack traces or internal details beyond TC12.
Extend security fuzzing and negative tests: include additional malicious inputs for query parameters, ensure comprehensive sanitization and consistent error messaging without sensitive data exposure.
Expand load and resilience tests: scale concurrent requests beyond 100, run stress tests that exercise downstream failures (DB, cache) and validate circuit-breaker / retry behavior and SLA adherence.
